Abstract

This paper presents and validates Cold Chip — a liquid-state computing architecture based on zero-heat-dissipation physical mechanisms. Unlike traditional power-saving approaches, Cold Chip eliminates the source of Joule heat generation at the architectural level rather than improving heat dissipation pathways. The core mechanism employs three layers: the transmission layer uses photonic waveguides and frictionless liquid-state tracks so that Q=I²Rt≡0; the switching layer uses micro-ring resonators to modulate refractive indices for logic switching without substantial current flow; the structural layer uses 0.5nm logic islands with liquid microfluidics for instantaneous heat absorption. The chip is 1mm², integrates 180,000 gates, and contains four functional islands (CPU/MEM/GPU/BUS) plus a central energy storage pool (ENG CORE). Five-step simulation verification was completed on EDA Playground (Icarus Verilog 12.0) with results directly observed by the user.

Key Results:
· Total power: 9,180 nW (49,216x lower than silicon baseline)
· Temperature rise: DeltaT = 0.000918K (near ambient)
· Energy recovery efficiency: EFF = 98.04% (Landauer physical limit)
· All five simulation verification steps passed

Keywords: Zero-heat dissipation; Liquid-state waveguide; Photonic computing; Non-dissipative architecture; Energy recycling; EFF=98.04%

